    <segment id="1" parent="19" relname="span">

Along with the ability to recover from an error the ability to report errors is important as well.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="12" relname="span"> One way we do this is by using a custom error reporting page, which is configured under IIS, </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="7" relname="circumstance">so that when an error that is not caught by the application</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="11" relname="span"> the details about that error are sent to the development team.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="15" relname="span"> 
Recently we took this process a step further.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="8" relname="circumstance"> When an error is generated </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="13" relname="span">a copy of the email is sent to our bug tracking software</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="13" relname="nonvolitional-result"> where it is automatically imported and worked until resolution.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="10" relname="circumstance"> 
In case anyone is interested</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="17" relname="span"> we&apos;re using FogBUGZ from Fogcreek software for our bug tracking.</segment>
